[{"data":1,"prerenderedAt":559},["ShallowReactive",2],{"header-locale:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2019\u002F10\u002F04\u002Fjs-reincarnation-19-this\u002F":3,"page:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2019\u002F10\u002F04\u002Fjs-reincarnation-19-this\u002F":4,"alt:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2019\u002F10\u002F04\u002Fjs-reincarnation-19-this\u002F":3,"prev-next:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2019\u002F10\u002F04\u002Fjs-reincarnation-19-this\u002F":534,"related:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2019\u002F10\u002F04\u002Fjs-reincarnation-19-this\u002F":543},"\u002Fjavascript\u002F20191004\u002F1360608032\u002F",{"id":5,"title":6,"abbrlink":7,"altUrl":3,"body":8,"category":517,"date":518,"description":519,"extension":520,"lang":521,"meta":522,"navigation":249,"path":523,"readingMinutes":524,"seo":525,"standalone":526,"stem":527,"tags":528,"tldr":531,"updated":518,"url":532,"__hash__":533},"content\u002Fen\u002FJavaScript\u002Fjs-reincarnation-19-this.md","EP.19 Learning JS From Zero — Day 19: Making Sense of this","1002106457",{"type":9,"value":10,"toc":509},"minimark",[11,16,28,32,35,48,56,63,91,118,122,177,191,195,260,274,280,284,298,355,358,384,387,475,480,486,492,498,502,505],[12,13,15],"h2",{"id":14},"intro","Intro",[17,18,19,20,24,25,27],"p",{},"Day 19 of my reincarnation, and this time we're going to talk about ",[21,22,23],"code",{},"this",". It's one of the most common keywords in JavaScript, and honestly one of the easiest to get burned by. So this post is all about what ",[21,26,23],{}," actually is.",[12,29,31],{"id":30},"can-you-eat-this","Can you eat this?",[17,33,34],{},"Let's back up a bit and talk about the execution environment first. JavaScript has what's called a creation phase. When that phase runs, JavaScript first creates two things:",[36,37,38,44],"ul",{},[39,40,41],"li",{},[21,42,43],{},"window",[39,45,46],{},[21,47,23],{},[17,49,50,52,53,55],{},[21,51,23],{}," is one of those things a lot of people trip over when they're learning JavaScript — and yeah, I've been burned by it plenty of times myself. So what is it, really? Let's just open the browser dev tools and type ",[21,54,23],{}," to see what we get.",[17,57,58],{},[59,60],"img",{"alt":61,"src":62},"window shows up","https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FNB8deax.png",[17,64,65,66,68,69,71,72,76,77,79,80,82,83,86,87,90],{},"So we can see that ",[21,67,23],{}," is the current ",[21,70,43],{},". Notice I said ",[73,74,75],"strong",{},"current"," — because right now ",[21,78,23],{}," happens to be referencing ",[21,81,43],{},". Why do I phrase it that way? Because ",[73,84,85],{},"this points to whatever the way you call it decides it points to",". Or you can think of it as ",[73,88,89],{},"this points to whatever the environment you call it in decides",". Keep both of those sentences in your head.",[17,92,93,94,96,97,99,100,102,103,105,106,108,109,111,112,114,115,117],{},"For example, when we just typed ",[21,95,23],{}," it showed ",[21,98,43],{},". That's because ",[21,101,23],{}," was called under ",[21,104,43],{},", so ",[21,107,23],{}," references ",[21,110,43],{},", which is why we got ",[21,113,43],{},". Let's run through a few examples to get a feel for ",[21,116,23],{},".",[12,119,121],{"id":120},"example-1","Example 1",[123,124,129],"pre",{"className":125,"code":126,"language":127,"meta":128,"style":128},"language-js shiki shiki-themes github-dark-high-contrast","var myname = '小明';\nconsole.log(this.myname); \u002F\u002F 小明\n","js","",[21,130,131,154],{"__ignoreMap":128},[132,133,136,140,144,147,151],"span",{"class":134,"line":135},"line",1,[132,137,139],{"class":138},"sWyjQ","var",[132,141,143],{"class":142},"sMAXC"," myname ",[132,145,146],{"class":138},"=",[132,148,150],{"class":149},"sTRMh"," '小明'",[132,152,153],{"class":142},";\n",[132,155,157,160,164,167,170,173],{"class":134,"line":156},2,[132,158,159],{"class":142},"console.",[132,161,163],{"class":162},"sj_SG","log",[132,165,166],{"class":142},"(",[132,168,23],{"class":169},"sCcAr",[132,171,172],{"class":142},".myname); ",[132,174,176],{"class":175},"sQrFR","\u002F\u002F 小明\n",[17,178,179,180,108,182,184,185,187,188,190],{},"Here ",[21,181,23],{},[21,183,43],{},", because the current ",[21,186,23],{}," is being called under ",[21,189,43],{},", so it can find 小明.",[12,192,194],{"id":193},"example-2","Example 2",[123,196,198],{"className":125,"code":197,"language":127,"meta":128,"style":128},"var myname = '小明';\nfunction fu () {\n  console.log(this.myname);\n}\n\nfu();\n",[21,199,200,212,223,238,244,251],{"__ignoreMap":128},[132,201,202,204,206,208,210],{"class":134,"line":135},[132,203,139],{"class":138},[132,205,143],{"class":142},[132,207,146],{"class":138},[132,209,150],{"class":149},[132,211,153],{"class":142},[132,213,214,217,220],{"class":134,"line":156},[132,215,216],{"class":138},"function",[132,218,219],{"class":162}," fu",[132,221,222],{"class":142}," () {\n",[132,224,226,229,231,233,235],{"class":134,"line":225},3,[132,227,228],{"class":142},"  console.",[132,230,163],{"class":162},[132,232,166],{"class":142},[132,234,23],{"class":169},[132,236,237],{"class":142},".myname);\n",[132,239,241],{"class":134,"line":240},4,[132,242,243],{"class":142},"}\n",[132,245,247],{"class":134,"line":246},5,[132,248,250],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":249},true,"\n",[132,252,254,257],{"class":134,"line":253},6,[132,255,256],{"class":162},"fu",[132,258,259],{"class":142},"();\n",[17,261,262,263,266,267,270,271,273],{},"This still finds the answer — still 小明. Just remember one thing here: ",[73,264,265],{},"this points to whatever the way you call it decides",". And we're calling ",[21,268,269],{},"fu();"," under ",[21,272,43],{},", so what's actually happening is this:",[17,275,276],{},[59,277],{"alt":278,"src":279},"小明","https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FqD5k1IY.png",[12,281,283],{"id":282},"example-3","Example 3",[17,285,286,287,289,290,293,294,297],{},"But basically there's one situation that'll make ",[21,288,23],{}," blow up with ",[21,291,292],{},"VM130:4 Uncaught TypeError: Cannot read property 'myname' of undefined",", and that's ",[21,295,296],{},"\"use strict\""," — strict mode. Using it is dead simple: just add it at the very top of your code and it kicks in.",[123,299,301],{"className":125,"code":300,"language":127,"meta":128,"style":128},"\"use strict\"\nvar myname = '小明';\nfunction fu () {\n  console.log(this.myname);\n}\n\nfu();\n",[21,302,303,308,320,328,340,344,348],{"__ignoreMap":128},[132,304,305],{"class":134,"line":135},[132,306,307],{"class":149},"\"use strict\"\n",[132,309,310,312,314,316,318],{"class":134,"line":156},[132,311,139],{"class":138},[132,313,143],{"class":142},[132,315,146],{"class":138},[132,317,150],{"class":149},[132,319,153],{"class":142},[132,321,322,324,326],{"class":134,"line":225},[132,323,216],{"class":138},[132,325,219],{"class":162},[132,327,222],{"class":142},[132,329,330,332,334,336,338],{"class":134,"line":240},[132,331,228],{"class":142},[132,333,163],{"class":162},[132,335,166],{"class":142},[132,337,23],{"class":169},[132,339,237],{"class":142},[132,341,342],{"class":134,"line":246},[132,343,243],{"class":142},[132,345,346],{"class":134,"line":253},[132,347,250],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":249},[132,349,351,353],{"class":134,"line":350},7,[132,352,256],{"class":162},[132,354,259],{"class":142},[17,356,357],{},"Per the ES5 spec, the gist is:",[359,360,361],"blockquote",{},[17,362,363,364,366,367,369,370,372,373,375,376,379,380,383],{},"In non-strict mode ",[21,365,23],{}," points to the global object (",[21,368,43],{},"), but in strict mode that's blocked for safety reasons. In short, the moment ",[21,371,23],{}," would point to the global (",[21,374,43],{},"), it becomes ",[21,377,378],{},"undefined"," instead — and you get the ",[21,381,382],{},"Cannot read property XXX of undefined"," error.",[17,385,386],{},"The fix is actually pretty simple: just change how you call it. For example, put the function and the variable inside an object and call the function through that object.",[123,388,390],{"className":125,"code":389,"language":127,"meta":128,"style":128},"\"use strict\"\nfunction fu () {\n  console.log(this.myname);\n}\n\nvar a = {\n  myname: '小明',\n  qq: fu,\n};\n\na.qq();\n",[21,391,392,396,404,416,420,424,436,447,453,459,464],{"__ignoreMap":128},[132,393,394],{"class":134,"line":135},[132,395,307],{"class":149},[132,397,398,400,402],{"class":134,"line":156},[132,399,216],{"class":138},[132,401,219],{"class":162},[132,403,222],{"class":142},[132,405,406,408,410,412,414],{"class":134,"line":225},[132,407,228],{"class":142},[132,409,163],{"class":162},[132,411,166],{"class":142},[132,413,23],{"class":169},[132,415,237],{"class":142},[132,417,418],{"class":134,"line":240},[132,419,243],{"class":142},[132,421,422],{"class":134,"line":246},[132,423,250],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":249},[132,425,426,428,431,433],{"class":134,"line":253},[132,427,139],{"class":138},[132,429,430],{"class":142}," a ",[132,432,146],{"class":138},[132,434,435],{"class":142}," {\n",[132,437,438,441,444],{"class":134,"line":350},[132,439,440],{"class":142},"  myname: ",[132,442,443],{"class":149},"'小明'",[132,445,446],{"class":142},",\n",[132,448,450],{"class":134,"line":449},8,[132,451,452],{"class":142},"  qq: fu,\n",[132,454,456],{"class":134,"line":455},9,[132,457,458],{"class":142},"};\n",[132,460,462],{"class":134,"line":461},10,[132,463,250],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":249},[132,465,467,470,473],{"class":134,"line":466},11,[132,468,469],{"class":142},"a.",[132,471,472],{"class":162},"qq",[132,474,259],{"class":142},[17,476,477],{},[59,478],{"alt":278,"src":479},"https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FLuqib00.png",[17,481,482,483,485],{},"So looking at the picture, ",[21,484,23],{}," is now pointing like this:",[17,487,488],{},[59,489],{"alt":490,"src":491},"this points to object a","https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002Foq9yXGX.png",[17,493,494,495,497],{},"So you can see that where ",[21,496,23],{}," points comes from how we call it. If we call it inside an object, it poin